    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and it mentioned lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles when u go hard and how the body gets rid of it afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you engage in high-intensity interval training (HIIT), your muscles rapidly consume oxygen, and to compensate, they start breaking down glucose for energy, which produces lactic acid as a byproduct. This process is called anaerobic glycolysis. The lactic acid accumulates in the muscle cells and can cause fatigue. The body then clears it out by converting it back to glucose in the liver through the Cori cycle, or it can be directly expelled through blood circulation once the oxygen levels are restored.",
