    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when people talk about that \"burn\" feeling during a set, is that literally just the acid sitting there, or is something else happening chemically that makes it feel like it's stinging? like what's the actual sensation mechanism?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"burn\" sensation isn't directly caused by lactic acid itself, but rather the accumulation of hydrogen ions (H+) that occurs alongside lactic acid production. As lactic acid builds up, it dissociates into lactate and H+. The increase in H+ concentration lowers the pH in your muscles, which can stimulate nerve endings and cause the burning sensation. Additionally, the buildup of H+ ions can interfere with the muscles' ability to contract, contributing to the feeling of fatigue and discomfort. As the body continues to work, it gradually clears the H+ ions, alleviating the sensation.",
      "source": "target",
